WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.720 --> 00:00:11.960
So, I hear you might be thinking about killing the author.

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:15.960
it’s an exciting time in any person’s
life when they’re deciding which literary

00:00:15.969 --> 00:00:20.330
theory to apply to the way they read texts,
but it’s important to know what you’re

00:00:20.330 --> 00:00:25.210
getting into, and make sure that this literary
theory is the right one for you.

00:00:25.210 --> 00:00:29.390
What is it about death of the author that
appeals to you, the reader? Before you start

00:00:29.390 --> 00:00:34.000
applying literary theories, you want to make
sure that you’re doing it for the right reasons.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.020
There are an awful lot of young people out
there who rush into death of the author without

00:00:38.020 --> 00:00:40.780
really understanding its intended purpose.

00:00:40.780 --> 00:00:45.210
Are you trying to enhance your understanding
of a text by secluding yourself from authorial

00:00:45.210 --> 00:00:48.980
intent or a body of work, or are you trying
to excuse yourself from potential guilt when

00:00:48.980 --> 00:00:53.960
you find out that your favorite author might
be a shitbag, and you don’t want to examine

00:00:53.960 --> 00:00:56.460
what that author does with their platform?

00:00:56.460 --> 00:01:01.210
There are a lot of people out there who advocate
separating art from the artist so they won’t

00:01:01.210 --> 00:01:05.439
have to examine the ethics of consuming art
from people who use their platform to do things

00:01:05.439 --> 00:01:08.350
that might be a little iffy.

00:01:08.350 --> 00:01:09.520
Maybe even harmful.

00:01:09.520 --> 00:01:14.100
Before we jump in, we need to understand that
applying a literary theory and examining the

00:01:14.100 --> 00:01:18.670
ethics of watching the usual suspects knowing
now what we know about its director and star

00:01:18.670 --> 00:01:20.190
are two very separate issues.

00:01:20.190 --> 00:01:25.620
And it can be confusing, and you need to be
careful not to conflate the two.

00:01:25.620 --> 00:01:29.670
With that in mind, let’s talk about death
of the author.

00:01:29.670 --> 00:01:34.100
Is death of the author right for you? Are
you ready to kill the author? And is death

00:01:34.100 --> 00:01:40.880
of the author really even possible to apply
to any text in our platform- and personal-brand-obsessed culture?

00:01:41.080 --> 00:01:46.120
Well today we’re going to talk about that,
learn a little something, and maybe...

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:48.680
even have a little fun.

00:02:04.150 --> 00:02:07.700
The fault in our stars is a 2012 novel written
by John Green.

00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:11.930
The plot of the novel revolves around two
teenagers named Hazel Grace Lancaster and

00:02:11.930 --> 00:02:16.769
Augustus Waters, the former living with terminal
cancer and the latter in remission from his,

00:02:16.769 --> 00:02:18.519
as they begin a relationship.

00:02:18.519 --> 00:02:22.470
In the process of developing their relationship,
Hazel Grace shares her favorite book of all

00:02:22.470 --> 00:02:26.989
time, "An Imperial Affliction" by a man named
Peter Van Houten, with Augustus.

00:02:26.989 --> 00:02:31.340
Though she loves the book, the book’s ambiguous
ending is a source of consternation for Hazel,

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:35.519
and she longs for nothing more than for the
notoriously reclusive Van Houten to tell her

00:02:35.519 --> 00:02:37.519
what happens after the book ends.

00:02:37.519 --> 00:02:41.829
And so Augustus, having banked his wish from
the make a wish foundation, uses that wish

00:02:41.829 --> 00:02:45.420
to make a trip to Amsterdam with hazel and
her mother to meet Van Houten.

00:02:45.860 --> 00:02:50.400
But when they finally meet Van Houten, the two
find not the kind, empathetic author that they

00:02:50.410 --> 00:02:54.019
imagined, but a drunken misanthrope who refuses
to answer their questions.

00:02:54.019 --> 00:02:57.810
"I can no more tell you what happens to her
than I can tell you what becomes of Proust's

00:02:57.810 --> 00:03:03.609
Narrator or Holden Caufield's sister or Huckleberry
Finn after he lights out for the territories"

00:03:03.609 --> 00:03:08.180
What happens after the book ends is nothing,
he insists. The book is fiction.

00:03:08.180 --> 00:03:09.189
It didn’t happen.

00:03:09.189 --> 00:03:10.469
It’s not real.

00:03:10.469 --> 00:03:12.480
To which a livid Hazel Grace responds:

00:03:12.480 --> 00:03:13.480
"BULLSHIT.

00:03:13.480 --> 00:03:15.060
That's bulllshit.

00:03:15.060 --> 00:03:16.110
Just tell me!

00:03:16.110 --> 00:03:18.150
Make something up!"

00:03:18.150 --> 00:03:21.730
Hazel has tied the idea that there is a life
for these characters after the book ends with

00:03:21.730 --> 00:03:25.760
her own narrative - she needs to believe that
there is a life for these characters

00:03:25.760 --> 00:03:30.790
beyond the text, because she sees so much
of herself in the text, right down to the

00:03:30.790 --> 00:03:33.290
protagonist living with terminal cancer.

00:03:33.290 --> 00:03:36.849
But in the end, the author of her favorite
book has no answer for her.

00:03:36.849 --> 00:03:41.799
And when, months later, feeling guilty about
the way their interaction had ended, Van Houten does

00:03:41.799 --> 00:03:46.879
come up with an answer, but Hazel no longer
wants to know - so neither she nor we, the

00:03:46.879 --> 00:03:49.169
reader, find out the fictional author’s
intent.

00:03:49.169 --> 00:03:54.260
Furthermore, "The Fault in our Stars" itself has
an ambiguous ending - we do not find out what

00:03:54.260 --> 00:03:59.379
becomes of Hazel Grace - how much longer,
if at all, Hazel survives her disease.

00:03:59.379 --> 00:04:03.129
As a solitary text unto itself, "The Fault
in our Stars" could be read as an argument

00:04:03.129 --> 00:04:05.140
in favor of death of the author.

00:04:05.140 --> 00:04:09.319
Not only is the author completely unlike what
the leads expect him to be, the author has

00:04:09.319 --> 00:04:10.569
no answers for them.

00:04:10.569 --> 00:04:15.529
Seeking his authorial intent is an exercise
in futility - the author has emotionally moved

00:04:15.529 --> 00:04:20.199
on from the book, and if he does have an answer
to Hazel’s question, he is not obligated

00:04:20.199 --> 00:04:21.200
to share it.

00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:26.500
But moreover, his intent does not matter - the
book does not speak to Hazel because of the

00:04:26.500 --> 00:04:29.440
author’s intent, but because of the text
itself.

00:04:29.440 --> 00:04:32.479
The text in isolation is what means so much
to Hazel.

00:04:32.479 --> 00:04:37.449
As a text, this seems to be the theme of "The Fault in our Stars"  - that a part of growing up is to stop

00:04:37.449 --> 00:04:42.490
looking to other people, especially authors,
to explain the meaning behind texts, but instead

00:04:42.490 --> 00:04:45.289
to figure out what your own reading is.

00:04:45.289 --> 00:04:49.699
Of course, we can’t know if this was the
author’s intent based on the text alone.

00:04:49.699 --> 00:04:54.840
Fortunately, thanks to the magic of the internet,
we do know exactly what the author thinks.

00:04:54.840 --> 00:05:00.319
In a 2014 tweet, Green got a lot of attention
and ten thousand retweets with the proclamation,

00:05:00.319 --> 00:05:02.590
“Books belong to their readers.”

00:05:02.590 --> 00:05:07.449
Green elaborated on that stance in an interview
in 2014: "I think authorial intent is pretty

00:05:07.449 --> 00:05:11.400
irrelevant, and I tend to agree with the school
of literary criticism that proclaims the death

00:05:11.400 --> 00:05:12.810
of the author."

00:05:12.810 --> 00:05:16.539
When pressed on what happens after the end
of "The Fault in our Stars" in a way that remarkably

00:05:16.539 --> 00:05:21.840
mirrors the way Hazel presses Van Houten,
Green stated in a now-deleted 2012 blog entry:

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:26.710
“I’m different from Peter Van Houten in
many important ways, but in this respect (and

00:05:26.710 --> 00:05:30.980
some others) we are the same: I have access
to the exact same text that you do.

00:05:30.980 --> 00:05:34.890
My thoughts about the world outside of that
text are not any more informed or authoritative

00:05:34.890 --> 00:05:35.890
than yours.

00:05:35.890 --> 00:05:37.060
It’s not my book.

00:05:37.060 --> 00:05:38.060
It’s your book.

00:05:38.060 --> 00:05:42.340
I don’t make decisions about things that
happen outside the text of the book; I can’t

00:05:42.340 --> 00:05:45.189
read something that isn’t there any more
than you can."

00:05:45.189 --> 00:05:50.389
It’s kind of rare to find an author with strong opinions on the concept of death of the author,

00:05:50.389 --> 00:05:53.850
who goes out of their way not only to avoid
making comments on what happens outside of

00:05:53.850 --> 00:05:57.610
the text, but to bake that very notion into
the text itself.

00:05:57.610 --> 00:06:00.610
But, of course, Green’s approach is not
the only one.

00:06:00.610 --> 00:06:04.979
If we’re talking about inserting authorial
intent into texts well after they have been

00:06:04.980 --> 00:06:09.040
published, then we need to talk about the
hippogriff in the room.

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:21.300
But first!

00:06:25.820 --> 00:06:28.680
In 1967, French literary critic and theorist,

00:06:28.820 --> 00:06:34.220
Roland Barthes published his essay, "La mort
de l’auteur," or “The Death of the Author,”

00:06:34.220 --> 00:06:36.300
which was published in English the following
year.

00:06:36.300 --> 00:06:40.250
The simplest reduction of the essay’s thesis
is that readers should pull away from the

00:06:40.250 --> 00:06:45.139
tenet of traditional literary criticism that
focused on authorial intent, and instead adopt

00:06:45.139 --> 00:06:49.960
a more text oriented approach that focused
on the interaction between the reader and the text,

00:06:49.960 --> 00:06:52.400
not between reader and the author.

00:06:52.400 --> 00:06:58.009
But to understand how this idea first came about--first,
we need to put ourselves into the headspace

00:06:58.009 --> 00:07:00.789
of French academia in the mid-1960s.

00:07:00.789 --> 00:07:06.340
Across academia, but particularly in Humanities-related
fields like literature, linguistics, philosophy,

00:07:06.340 --> 00:07:10.939
and anthropology, we were seeing a trend away
from a Structuralist methodology--i.e., a

00:07:10.939 --> 00:07:15.780
methodology that saw facets of human culture
as intrinsically related to a broader, overarching

00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:19.759
system or structure--
By the 1960s, academia had now saw itself

00:07:19.759 --> 00:07:24.199
trending towards a “post-structuralist”
point of view, fueled by thinkers like Foucalt,

00:07:24.200 --> 00:07:27.140
Barthes, and my good friend Derrida.

00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:31.300
Post-structuralism questioned the more binary
relationship of structuralism--that you couldn’t

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:37.710
make X assumption about X person/social group/work
of art just because X person came from a certain

00:07:37.710 --> 00:07:42.120
place, experienced a certain thing, spoke
a certain language, ate a certain thing for

00:07:42.120 --> 00:07:44.039
breakfast, etc.

00:07:44.039 --> 00:07:49.099
And if it’s beginning to sound like “post-structuralism”
involves a lot of complicated French naval-gazing

00:07:49.099 --> 00:07:51.849
academic bloviating, that’s because it does.

00:07:51.849 --> 00:07:55.770
But for the purposes of keeping this short
and sweet, we’ll keep our discussion of

00:07:55.770 --> 00:08:00.129
post-structuralism contained to where it concerns
Barthes, and novelists.

00:08:00.129 --> 00:08:04.060
In "Death of the Author," Barthes argues that
“Writing is that neutral, composite, oblique

00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:08.819
space where our subject slips away, the negative
where all identity is lost, starting with

00:08:08.819 --> 00:08:11.689
the very identity of the body writing.”

00:08:11.689 --> 00:08:15.979
In other words, Barthes argues that a piece
of text is fundamentally divorced from the

00:08:15.979 --> 00:08:16.979
author who made it.

00:08:16.979 --> 00:08:20.199
And if it seems like a simple concept now,
keep in mind:

00:08:20.199 --> 00:08:25.020
In particular to the literary and visual arts,
up until the 1960s, much of a creator’s work

00:08:25.020 --> 00:08:29.669
in academia was examined through a lense that
tied together said creator and their life.

00:08:29.669 --> 00:08:33.290
Biography was king in helping to interpret
or understand a work of art.

00:08:33.290 --> 00:08:36.010
Take, for example, William Shakespeare’s
"Macbeth."

00:08:36.010 --> 00:08:39.540
Traditional readings of the text would argue
that an understanding of both Scottish history

00:08:39.540 --> 00:08:43.840
and Shakespeare’s life are fundamental in
understanding the play itself-- how it pays

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:47.290
homage to King James I, who was king while
it was being written, and how it reflects

00:08:47.290 --> 00:08:51.150
the king’s relationship to the author--King
James was also the patron of Shakespeare’s

00:08:51.150 --> 00:08:52.660
acting company at the time.

00:08:52.660 --> 00:08:56.700
But for Barthes, none of this background information
would be pertinent in reading "Macbeth."

00:08:56.700 --> 00:09:00.970
Meaning, to Barthes, lies in the language
of a text itself and whatever impressions

00:09:00.970 --> 00:09:02.350
the reader creates from it.

00:09:02.350 --> 00:09:05.340
The Author is less of a God and more of a
mere scriptor.

00:09:05.340 --> 00:09:09.540
And according to Barthes’s contemporary Foucault, ”The
work, which once had the duty of providing

00:09:09.540 --> 00:09:13.720
immortality, now possesses the right to kill,
to be its author’s murderer.”

00:09:15.240 --> 00:09:16.700
Does it though?

00:09:22.150 --> 00:09:26.210
French literary theorists in the mid to late
1960’s probably weren’t too concerned

00:09:26.210 --> 00:09:31.290
with pop cultural fanworks and their relation
not only to text, but to authorial intent

00:09:31.290 --> 00:09:35.580
and the author’s body of work, in no small
part because it was not an organized Thing

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:38.200
in the way it would be only a decade later.

00:09:38.200 --> 00:09:42.220
But in discussions of death of the author
and pop culture media, the interaction between

00:09:42.220 --> 00:09:44.330
author and fans is extremely relevant.

00:09:44.330 --> 00:09:49.890
Take, for instance, a writer like Anne Rice,
who takes an unusually hardline stance on

00:09:49.890 --> 00:09:52.330
fanworks, especially fan fiction:

00:09:52.330 --> 00:09:56.100
From Rice’s official website: "I do not
allow fan fiction.

00:09:56.100 --> 00:09:57.630
The characters are copyrighted.

00:09:57.630 --> 00:10:01.230
It upsets me terribly to even think about
fan fiction with my characters.

00:10:01.230 --> 00:10:05.220
I advise my readers to write your own original
stories with your own characters.

00:10:05.220 --> 00:10:08.770
It is absolutely essential that you respect
my wishes."

00:10:08.770 --> 00:10:10.920
RESPECT THE AUTHOR’S WISHES, FANS.

00:10:10.920 --> 00:10:12.940
HOW DARE YOU MAKE THE GAY VAMPIRES EVEN GAYER?

00:10:12.940 --> 00:10:17.570
And Rice was not fucking around either. To be in
Anne Rice fandom in the mid-2000’s was to

00:10:17.570 --> 00:10:22.370
play a dangerous game of threats of C&amp;D’s
and of litigation, and the near sum totality

00:10:22.370 --> 00:10:27.480
of fanworks relating to the vampire chronicles
existed in locked down private livejournal groups.

00:10:28.040 --> 00:10:32.280
I bring up Rice because on some level, she
has a lot in common with "Harry Potter" author,

00:10:32.290 --> 00:10:36.200
JK Rowling, but in this one crucial regard,
they are miles apart.

00:10:36.200 --> 00:10:40.300
From the onset of Harry Potter’s popularity,
JK Rowling has shown an interest in engaging

00:10:40.300 --> 00:10:46.150
with the fandom and, at most times, been downright
encouraging of fanworks, not limited to fan

00:10:46.150 --> 00:10:50.810
art, fan fiction, fan resource sites, and
other things created by her audience.

00:10:50.810 --> 00:10:54.940
Said Rowling’s agent at Christopher Little
Publishing, “JK Rowling's reaction is that

00:10:54.940 --> 00:10:59.150
she is very flattered by the fact there is
such great interest in her Harry Potter series

00:10:59.150 --> 00:11:01.640
and that people take the time to write their
own stories.”

00:11:02.060 --> 00:11:06.080
So, at a surface level, this seems like an
ideal creator-audience relationship: Your

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:09.510
favorite author is not only fine with you
and your Tumblr friends writing stories about

00:11:09.510 --> 00:11:13.170
her characters, but she’s an open book when
it comes to answering any and all pedantic

00:11:13.170 --> 00:11:15.140
nerd questions you might have about your faves.

00:11:15.380 --> 00:11:17.240
What could go wrong with that?

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:23.000
Well largely, it’s the one thing she has
in common with Rice, namely the sense that

00:11:23.010 --> 00:11:26.360
they are masters of the universe that they created
as authors -

00:11:26.360 --> 00:11:30.500
Ever since she joined Twitter, Rowling has
had a tendency to post-scripturally insert

00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:35.631
context, meaning and intent into her text
long after the text has been published, which

00:11:35.631 --> 00:11:39.250
many fans love, but just as many take issue
with.

00:11:39.250 --> 00:11:43.730
Not just because of injecting non-textual
intent, but because some of that intent comes

00:11:43.730 --> 00:11:46.920
laden with #implications.

00:11:46.940 --> 00:11:52.360
Like, sure, we get that lycanthropy is a stand-in
for disease stigmatization, but Rowling

00:11:52.361 --> 00:11:57.860
double-downing on it and then explicitly stating
that it is a wizarding world AIDS analog while

00:11:57.860 --> 00:12:02.820
making one of the main werewolves in the series
essentially a child predator with the explicit

00:12:02.820 --> 00:12:07.080
evil intent of infecting people with his disease
is...

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:13.400
And then there’s Dumbledore.

00:12:14.080 --> 00:12:18.731
At a public reading of the then recently published
last book in the series, "Harry Potter and

00:12:18.731 --> 00:12:23.660
The Deathly Hollows," when a fan asked if Dumbledore
had ever loved anyone, Rowling responded:

00:12:23.660 --> 00:12:27.500
'My truthful answer to you...I always thought
of Dumbledore as gay...

00:12:27.680 --> 00:12:29.020
and that added to his horror when

00:12:29.020 --> 00:12:31.880
Grindelwald showed himself to be what he was.

00:12:31.880 --> 00:12:35.920
To an extent, do we say it excused Dumbledore
a little more because falling in love can

00:12:35.920 --> 00:12:41.250
blind us to an extent, but he met someone
as brilliant as he was and, rather like Bellatrix,

00:12:41.250 --> 00:12:46.130
he was very drawn to this brilliant person
and horribly, terribly let down by him.'

00:12:46.130 --> 00:12:48.460
She added: 'Yeah, that's how I always saw
Dumbledore.

00:12:49.220 --> 00:12:55.471
And even in 2007, that kind of intent declaration
was already begging the question if representation

00:12:55.471 --> 00:13:00.130
just for representation’s sake, especially
when there is no actual reference in the text

00:13:00.130 --> 00:13:04.910
to Dumbledore’s sexuality, was actually
helpful or if it was just shoehorned tokenizing

00:13:04.910 --> 00:13:07.410
for the sake of staying relevant.

00:13:07.410 --> 00:13:12.160
It is, in effect, claiming representation
without having to do any of the work of including

00:13:12.160 --> 00:13:13.740
it in the text, because hey.

00:13:13.740 --> 00:13:15.860
Authorial intent.

00:13:16.040 --> 00:13:20.940
And yet, after all this, despite multiple opportunities to codify Dumbledore’s

00:13:20.940 --> 00:13:25.190
sexuality into the actual text, she still
hasn’t done it.

00:13:25.190 --> 00:13:28.870
Rowling had the opportunity to actually codify
this into later texts, as she is the sole

00:13:28.870 --> 00:13:33.300
credited writer for both Fantastic Beasts
movies, the latter of which touches directly

00:13:33.300 --> 00:13:39.560
on Dumbledore’s angst over his relationship
with Grindelwald but… no homo.

00:13:39.740 --> 00:13:44.640
LGBT representation in the Harry Potter-verse
exists only in the paratext, in the authorial

00:13:44.640 --> 00:13:48.770
intent - therefore, according to Barthes,
it does not exist at all.

00:13:48.770 --> 00:13:53.420
That said, of course authorial intent influences
fan culture, and inevitably creeps into the

00:13:53.420 --> 00:13:58.740
way people read the text - people take authorial intent
as word of god, and use it to shut down readings

00:13:58.740 --> 00:14:01.760
that conflict with the authorial’s post-scriptural
intent.

00:14:02.180 --> 00:14:04.080
And that... kind of sucks.

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:08.660
It’s all well and good - and valid - to
restrict discourse on the Harry Potter series

00:14:08.700 --> 00:14:11.680
to the text itself, and not what the author
says about the text.

00:14:11.900 --> 00:14:17.220
But here’s the thing - that is neither how
consuming art nor human nature works.

00:14:17.220 --> 00:14:22.020
Text is inevitably consumed with paratext
- and paratext influences the way the reader

00:14:22.020 --> 00:14:23.980
interprets the text.

00:14:23.980 --> 00:14:28.610
Simply knowing the Discourse around Harry
Potter influences the way you read Harry Potter

00:14:28.610 --> 00:14:31.440
- whether you want it to, or not.

00:14:39.780 --> 00:14:46.060
In literary theory, paratext refers to materials
supplied by authors, editors, printers and publishers.

00:14:46.340 --> 00:14:50.700
This concept has more recently expanded to
anything relating to the text - ranging all

00:14:50.700 --> 00:14:57.250
the way from cultural context to personal brand to size and nature of online platform and, most importantly,

00:14:57.250 --> 00:14:58.730
to personal identity.

00:14:58.730 --> 00:15:03.390
It’s not that trying to apply Barthes's idea
is invalid, but that given the way culture

00:15:03.390 --> 00:15:07.951
is trending and how the focus on personal
brand and identity is only increasing, even

00:15:07.951 --> 00:15:12.290
an author that tries to let their work speak
for itself can never really die.

00:15:12.290 --> 00:15:17.240
Foucault was actually way more hardcore than
