Yeah, you at least feel a connection to the way that they imagined something, which is intimate in a way.

00:23:08.400 --> 00:23:11.800
And I don't know that there's any getting around that.

00:23:15.520 --> 00:23:22.560
And so the question for me is how do authors interact with stories that they've invented in this time?

00:23:22.900 --> 00:23:28.060
I feel like the idea of death of the author kind of stemmed partially from

00:23:28.280 --> 00:23:34.320
this culture that was very absolute, and Bathes kind of wanted to kill absolutes.

00:23:34.460 --> 00:23:37.480
But in return, it kind of created a different absolute.

00:23:37.760 --> 00:23:44.860
I used to believe that the author should disappear insofar as possible from the text and that the responsibility

00:23:44.980 --> 00:23:50.140
of the reader was to read the text and never think about the author.

00:23:50.340 --> 00:23:55.360
You know, like, I had this period in high school where I read everything in the context of the author.

00:23:55.440 --> 00:24:01.600
