just putting a note in the beginning that says don't read this autobiographically is gonna work

00:26:04.140 --> 00:26:07.960
The Fault in Our Stars is a 2012 novel written by John Green ,

00:26:07.980 --> 00:26:15.040
in which two children go to great lengths to find out what happens after the ambiguous ending of the protagonist Hazel’s favorite book.

00:26:15.380 --> 00:26:21.200
The way they do this is to seek out the notoriously reclusive author, and find out the answer from him.

00:26:21.480 --> 00:26:29.740
But the entire idea is flawed from the getgo - not only does her hero let her down, she does not find her answer, because there is none,

00:26:29.880 --> 00:26:38.880
and that is a central theme of the text - sometimes, there is no answer, the universe is chaotic, life is unpredictable and you have no control of when you will die,

00:26:38.980 --> 00:26:43.680
and when you die you will not know what becomes of your loved ones.

00:26:43.800 --> 00:26:50.380
In seeking out the authorial intent behind a work of fiction, the two leads are trying to gain a sense of control in a chaotic universe,

00:26:50.580 --> 00:27:00.140
the sense that there is indeed an author of sorts to life, as they do not feel that they are the authors of their own stories, that they do not have control over their own fates.

00:27:00.240 --> 00:27:06.260
And indeed they do not - but in this case,
letting go of that desire for a sense of control

00:27:06.270 --> 00:27:11.640
is a part of growing up, which ironically,
neither of these characters will get to do.

00:27:11.640 --> 00:27:15.350
They must mature into adults while never living
to become adults.

00:27:15.350 --> 00:27:21.320
This is reflective not only of how we consume
media and the way media can genuinely touch

00:27:21.320 --> 00:27:27.190
and inspire people, but also of a very understandable
and human desire to transform that media.

00:27:27.190 --> 00:27:32.210
Narratives give us a sense of control in a
world that is generally chaotic and unpredictable.

00:27:32.210 --> 00:27:34.790
We need narratives to make sense of the world that we live in.

00:27:34.790 --> 00:27:38.450
But that does not mean that we have control
over the narrative.

00:27:38.450 --> 00:27:43.230
The character arcs of both Hazel and Augustus
are defined by letting go of that desire for

00:27:43.230 --> 00:27:49.559
control of their own narratives, and accepting
that life, short though it is, just doesn’t

00:27:49.560 --> 00:27:52.940
work that way, no matter how much they wish
it did.

00:27:53.680 --> 00:27:56.400
But that’s just my reading.

